INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '3f794c06-b273-4040-81fd-07fae3dafeb5',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$DVC as an Offline Feature Store — Versioned Features with dvc.api$escape$,
  $escape$DVC doesn't ship a feature store, but its pipeline and artifact model cover the offline half cleanly. Define feature engineering as a `dvc stage` in `dvc.yaml`, declare raw data as `deps` and computed features as `outs` with `cache: true`. DVC hashes each output and syncs it to your remote (S3, GCS, Azure Blob) — every `git commit` becomes an immutable feature snapshot.

At training time, `dvc.api.open()` fetches the exact feature parquet tied to a Git revision — no 'which features did we train on?' archaeology. Pin a revision to a model experiment via `dvc exp run` and feature provenance travels with the run automatically.

For online features, DVC alone isn't sufficient — you need a low-latency serving layer (Redis, Feast, a custom FastAPI endpoint). The bridge: after `dvc pull`, export the versioned offline features and hydrate your online store during the deployment step. DVC becomes the source of truth for feature schemas and historical values; the online store handles sub-millisecond reads at inference time. This split keeps retraining reproducible without coupling it to online serving infrastructure.$escape$,
  $escape$# dvc.yaml — offline feature pipeline
# stages:
#   build_features:
#     cmd: python src/features.py
#     deps: [data/raw/events.parquet, src/features.py]
#     outs:
#       - data/features/user_features.parquet: {cache: true}

import dvc.api
import pandas as pd

# Fetch feature snapshot pinned to a specific Git revision
with dvc.api.open(
    "data/features/user_features.parquet",
    rev="v1.3.0",  # Git tag tied to experiment
    mode="rb",
) as f:
    offline_features = pd.read_parquet(f)

# Hydrate online store (e.g. Redis) after dvc pull in CI
feature_records = offline_features.to_dict("index")$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
